And it all began with Bob Clampett's take on the Dick Tracy" comic series, 1936's "The Great Piggy Bank Robbery" http://www. dailymotion.com/video/x5z3uw4"
The 2 events that took CN to another level was debut of Space Ghost Coast 2 Coast" in 94 & launch of the "World Premiere Toons" in 95."
Over next few yrs, CN grew thru combination of retransmission packaging & simulcasting. Helping it grow past it's initial 233 cable systems.
The network's initial content was pre-1948 WB shorts, Popeye from 1933-57, the MGM cartoon library, & the Hanna-Barbera library.
The network was initially only seen in Philly, NYC, Washington D.C., and Detroit. A small footprint considering it being a Turner network.
At Noon, October 1st, 1992, after a playing of the SSB, Ted Turner blew up a stick of dynamite and @cartoonnetwork went on the air.
25 years ago today, Ted Turner launched his 5th cable network, based off his 1986 MGM/UA buy and his 1991 buy of Hanna-Barbera.

Sure, Korrasami kicked down so many doors others have waltzed thru since. But fact is LOK's overall story flaws make it inferior to ATLA.
I put my fantasy Book 4 up b/c Korra not having an overarching story that connects the books together is what makes it inferior to ATLA.
Plus, having EQUALISTS as Book 4's antagonists instead of Kuvira would also make Hiroshi's sacrifice more powerful & bring him full circle.
You have Equalists with Kuvira's tech and followers in all corners of the globe ready to fight? That raises the stakes.
The problem w/Kuvira is that she was built as a big bad but in fact only threatened the Earth Kingdom and never threatened any other nation.
And the end of Chapter 1 has the new Equalist leader come up and announce that she's going after the other nations with their new Tech.
Also, Bk4 would have a longer timeskip from 3 and would open w/Kuvira and the Earth Kingdom in place...only to fall in an Equalist revolt.
And I'd turn Zaofu/Suyin into part of the problem as they should be, having Equalists utilize fact Zaofu didn't help to their advantage.
But unlike Amon, the new leader does NOT wear a mask and does NOT hide herself in any way. This makes her a lot more dangerous.
It is this new Equalist movement, built and cultivated underground thru the events of the previous 3 books, that is the final villain.
We then cut to Lieutenant kneeling and speaking with a new Equalist leader, FEMALE, who filled Amon's and rebuilt the structure underground.
So, we head to end of Bk3. Korra's out of commission, and the Red Lotus unleashed chaos that's still being felt despite the RL's defeat.
And between Amon being a bender, Book 2's Water Tribe civil war, and the Red Lotus causing chaos, there's STILL a lot to hate about Benders.
No, simply having a non-bending Pres. of Repub City is NOT going to do the job. Fact is BENDERS are still the dominant force in the world.
Firstly, I'd tweak books 2 and 3 to NOT have Equalism be swept under the rug after Amon's exposure as a bender.
Now that I think about it, Bk3 was the only season where there was actual consequences that weren't fixed with an ex machina. https:// twitter.com/TheRealDonEast /status/908720350183219205 …
If it were me, I'd keep Book 2 and 3 as is (w/tweaking of course), but have Equalists in the shadows waiting for the moment to rise again.
And as Enter points out, the exposing of Amon being a Bender should've ENHANCED Pro-Equalist sentiment.
And yes, I firmly believe that the Equalist storyline being dumped after Book 1 like it was nothing was a mistake.
And yes, Book 1 would've benefited more if the ProBending and Love Triangle stuff was replaced by building up Amon and the Equalists.
@MysteriousEnter really does a stellar job of going under Book 1's hood and exposing the flaws: https://www. youtube.com/watch?v=J1ekVc Fsa2A …
Look, I'm a big big fan of Korrasami. But we can't deny HOW Bryke did this and how it was done with plenty of flaws.
And they tried to fix issues in these stories fixed w/plot convenience bandages, but it failed since the issues were still readily apparent.
That, quite frankly, is Korra's biggest flaw. It's 4 different stories with the same core of characters and plenty o' flaws about.
I think the real issue with Korra is that Bryke decided that instead of one over-arching storyline like ATLA there were 4 different stories.
And of course, Book 4's Kuvira didn't really feel like a villain out of the box and they had to force in the villainy.
Book 3 was a Rules vs Anarchy bit that was wayyyyy too dark and didn't have a true finality.
The Water Tribe Civil War" of Book 2 devolved into a Spirit vs Spirit fight that also added a "End of the Avatar Line" element."
Mr. Enter went thru the story flaws in Book 1, but the other books aren't that much better if you think about it.

Fox regretted the move and thus in September '96 it forced KTVI to buck trend of it's fellow New World stations and air Fox Kids.

On KNLC's side, the station was plagued by the fact it was unviewable in much of the market, even on cable.

Fox especailly b/c KNLC decided not to sell ad slots locally because of the internal objections to both the ads & the programming itself.

This is a time period in which it was also airing first-run & off-network secular syndicated programs as well.
Enter KNLC, the religious station owned by the New Life Evangelistic Center. It stepped in & aired FoxKids both wkdays and wknds.
KTVI decided to opt out of running Fox Kids programming in order to run extended newscasts, which left Fox looking for a station to air it.
